In [49]:
# Correlation Heatmap function
def plot_corr(df, size=11):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')
In [50]:

In [52]:
# Spliting the data into training and test set in the ratio of 70:30
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = df_model[['Income',  'Family', 'CCAvg' , 'Education_Undergrad', 'Education_Graduate', 'Education_Undergrad', 'Mortgage', 'CD Account']]
Y = df_model[['Personal Loan']]

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
x_train.head()

In [53]:
# Fit the model on train
model = LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear")
model.fit(x_train, y_train)
#predict on test
y_predict = model.predict(x_test)


coef_df = pd.DataFrame(model.coef_)
coef_df['intercept'] = model.intercept_
In [54]:
# Fining the accuracy of the model by applying test data on it
print(f'Training Accuracy is {model.score(x_train, y_train) * 100}%')

In [63]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

logit_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test))
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
plt.figure()
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='Logistic Regression (area = %0.2f)' % logit_roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.savefig('Log_ROC')
plt.show()
In [56]:
# heatmap to display confusion matrix
cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predict, labels=[1, 0])

df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["1","0"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["Predicted 1","Predicted 0"]])
plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt = ".1f");

Insights from the confusion matrix:

  • We can see there are 7 False positives, 54 False negetives
  • Rest of the predictions and outcomes are in sync
  • In the case of personal loan this is a high level of accuracy as from the target audience only small % (7 people) is a miss
  • Although 54 people are miscategorized, it is not a big number when compared to the sample size.

Business Insights

  • Here the bank wants to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget. In other words the bank wants to predict with relatively high accuracy as to which of their liability customers are most likely to take a personal loan.
  • In this case I think Recall and roc AUC score are important parameters to judge the effectiveness of the model.
  • Increasing the threshold to the inflution point which is approx .85 could be a good idea if the bank wants even better results for the model.
  • In my view the false negetives are pretty low for the sample size and because this is a model to assist effective marketing , the bank does not stand to lose a lot of money with the current accuracy achieved.
